		<description><![CDATA[I really liked your &#039;next shiny object&#039; analogy: it is so true, as I found when learning saxophone. There is no substitute for a good grounding in the fundamentals. Joe Hubbard uses the analogy of trying to run before you can walk, and he also talks of the &#039;Swiss cheese guys&#039;: players who can play but have a lot of holes in their understanding because they didn&#039;t absorb the fundamentals.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I really liked your &#8216;next shiny object&#8217; analogy: it is so true, as I found when learning saxophone. There is no substitute for a good grounding in the fundamentals. Joe Hubbard uses the analogy of trying to run before you can walk, and he also talks of the &#8216;Swiss cheese guys&#8217;: players who can play but have a lot of holes in their understanding because they didn&#8217;t absorb the fundamentals.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
